taxonomicNotes: Jackiewicz (1998) states that there are several problems concerning the nomenclature of the family Lymnaeidae, and that there is probably no other snail group in such taxonomical disarray. Stagnicola has been used as a synonym for Lymnaea by various authors, and as a subgenus of Lymnaea by others (Ponder and Waterhouse 1997, Vinarski 2003, NatureServe 2009). Hovingh (1993) lists this species as Lymnaea (Stagnicola) pilsbryi, whereas NatureServe (2009) name it Stagnicola pilsbryi. Dillon (2009) suggests that Lymnaea pilsbryi is a synonym of Lymnaea humilis, but this is neither supported or denied in other literature. Stagnicola is used by Turgeon et al. (1998) in the most recent list. However, Hubendick (1951) used Lymnaea. For the purpose of this assessment, we follow the taxonomy used by NatureServe.
Ou and Yeo (1995) consider that Macrobrachium leptodactylus is a synonym of M. pilimanus.

Garman reported a single female collected by E. Palmer in the early 1890's from a spring or endorheic stream near Parras, Coahuila, but regarded it as Characodon lateralis. Jordan and Evermann, however, restricted lateralis to Central America following the designation given by Günther and renamed this individual from Parras Characodon garmani without examinating it. Meek again used the name Characodon garmani for individuals from the Mezquital river, too, as the name Characodon lateralis was occupied for fish from "lowland streams from Central America, north to the state of Jalisco". This directly led to Regan synonymizing both species as Characodon lateralis, as he couldn't find any difference between them (as, except for this single female, all fish came from the Mezquital drainage). Finally, it was Smith and Miller (1983) who re-examined the Holotype of garmani and accepted the species as valid.
This has been recognised as a subspecies of Elimia catonaria. But is in AFS list. A. Bogan comments that other subspecies are also present: E. pastelli (Lea, 1858).

The previous Red List assessments for Galápagos tortoises treated the various allopatric island populations as subspecies of Chelonoidis nigra (now named Chelonoidis niger), as did several authors (Pritchard 1996, Caccone et al. 1999, Beheregaray et al. 2003, Fritz and Havas 2007,TTWG 2007, Rhodin et al. 2008). However, other authors have considered them as full species based on morphology (Bour 1980, Fritts 1983, Ernst and Barbour 1989) and the more recent consensus among researchers (Caccone et al. 2002; Russello et al. 2005, 2007; Poulakakis et al. 2008, 2012, 2015; Chiari et al. 2009) is to treat most as full species based on congruent patterns of mitochondrial and nuclear variation. This elevated species-level taxonomy has been largely accepted by TTWG (2009, 2014) and TEWG (2015) for most, but not all, phylogenetic lineages of Galápagos tortoises. This Red List assessment therefore now treats C. niger as a full species, rather than retaining its previous subspecies ranking from earlier Red List assessments. This species from Floreana has also been referred to in some recent literature as C. elephantopus, but that name is a nomen dubium (TTWG 2009) and should not be used for the this species. The spelling of the specific name was recently changed from nigra to niger as a result of the determination that the gender of the generic name Chelonoidis is actually masculine rather than feminine (Olson and David 2014).

Athearnia crassa was formerly placed as a subspecies of Leptoxis (= Athearnia) crassa (see Dillon and Ahlstedt 1997). Athearnia crassa crassa and Athearnia crassa anthonyi are distinct from one another and Athearnia anthonyi and Athearnia crassa are now recognized as distinct species (see Dillon and Ahlstedt 1997; Minton and Savarese 2005).

Appeared in IUCN Red Lists from 1996 to 2006 under the incorrectly spelt name Leptoxis crassa. Was also incorrectly listed as Vulnerable.
May be Bythinia dulvertonensis Tenison-Woods, 1876 which is a synonym of Austropyrgus simsonianus (Brazier, 1875).

scientificName: Oncorhynchus nerka COLUMBIA RIVER: Yakima R
taxonomicNotes:
A total of 93 extant and five extinct subpopulations were identified across the natural range of O. nerka. The assessors used a combination of ecoregional information (i.e., based on differences in marine and freshwater habitat) and the degree of genetic divergence between known spawning locations, using an Fst value of 0.04, representing a threshold level of gene flow between putative subpopulations of less than or equal to one effective migrant per year. The five extinct subpopulations were based on Gustafson et al. 2007. While the assessors acknowledge that it is not straightforward to ascribe demographic or geographic distinctness to a subpopulation based on observed genetic distances, they feel it is the most appropriate methodology given the scale of the assessment and the paucity of observations of stray rates among the spawning locations considered in this assessment. For the amendment completed in 2011, we split a number of British Columbia subpopulations described in the original 2008 assessment based on additional input from experts.  For a complete description of the approach and methods used for identifying units and the underlying assumptions, please refer to the supplementary material.

Subpopulation naming convention:
Subpopulation names consist of an ecoregion name in upper case with any subdivision of the ecoregion by other criteria (e.g. genetic divergence) indicated in proper case after a colon.

Salvelinus profundus is only known from Lake Constance. Other populations of deep-water charrs belong to other species.
Earlier considered to be a subspecies of R. kessleri.
This species' taxonomic status is unclear, and it may be a synonym of the congener G. aculeatus.

The International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature (2003) ruled that the name Bos primigenius for this wild species is not invalid by virtue of being antedated by the name based on the domestic form. Therefore, IUCN considers the wild species of Aurochs under the name Bos primigenius, while the domestic forms of cattle are considered under Bos taurus (see Gentry et al. 2004). Grubb (2005) lists B. primigenius as a subspecies of B. taurus, contrary to most authors, but we do not follow that arrangement here.
Radoman (1985) considered this species to be distinct from the other five taxa in genus Ohridohauffenia and its distribution is different based on the distributional data given in Radoman (1985).
There are taxonomic issues relating to identity of the species in the genus Bythinella, but these can only be resolved with live specimens, and this species has not been recorded for over 50 years.
This species was confused with Partula clarkei. P. turgida probably became extinct in the 1990s. The captive population was P. clarkei.
The status of this species has been disputed and Johnson, Murray and Clarke (1992) believed that it may have been a sinistral variety of P. affinis, however this similarity is only superficial.
This species is suspected to be of hybrid origin and it is doubtful whether this is a distinct species.

Cope (1885) used both Cyclura onchiopsis and Cyclura nigerrima; but only the former was diagnosed. Consequently, the latter must was a nomen nudum. Nearly a year later, Cope (1885 [1886]) provided a diagnosis for C. nigerrima. Barbour (1937) relegated C. nigerrima to a subspecies of C. cornuta. Schwartz and Carey (1977) formally placed C. nigerrima in the synonymy of C. onchiopsis.

Originally described as a full species, the Navassa Rhinoceros Iguana was relegated to subspecific status within the Rhinoceros Iguanas (Cyclura cornuta) first by Cope (1885 [1886]), without presenting any evidence other than superficial physical similarity. That status was contradicted by Barbour and Noble (1916), although Barbour (1937) later reverted to the subspecific designation. Carey (1977) recognized Cyclura onchiopsis as a full species, but most subsequent authorities followed Schwartz and Thomas (1975) in recognizing it as a subspecies. Powell (1999) re-elevated the taxon to full species status.
Platytropius siamensis was described from the Chao Phraya River in Bangkok (Sauvage 1883) as a species of Pseudeutropius. Hora (1937) subsequently erected the genus Platytropius for this species.
The generic position is uncertain in absence of anatomical data.
The name of the family Mutelidae has been altered in Iridinidae.
The generic position is uncertain due to lack of anatomical data. Synonymisation according to Boeters (1976).
The generic status is uncertain due to lack of anatomical data. The taxonomy of the hydrobiids of Algeria has not been revised since 1864.
The generic position is uncertain due to lack of anatomical data. Synonymisation according to Boeters (1976).
The generic status is uncertain due to lack of anatomical study.
The generic position is uncertain due to lack of anatomical data.
The generic position uncertain in absence of anatomical data. Synonymisation based on Boeters (1976)

The generic position is uncertain due to lack of anatomical data. According to Boeters (1976) the shells from Goulette (Tunisia) identified by Letourneux and Bourguignat (1887) as B. microcochlia belong to a different species. They are hence not incorporated in this assessment.
The generic position is uncertain due to lack of anatomical data. Synonymisation according to Boeters (1976).
Generic position uncertain by lack of anatomical data. Synonymisation according to Boeters (1976), but here considered a distinct species.
The generic position is uncertain in absence of anatomical data. Synonymisation based on Boeters (1976)

This is a distinct species, possibly new genus. The generic status is uncertain due to lack of anatomical data. The taxonomy of the hydrobiids of Algeria has not been revised since 1864.

Glöer et al. (2010) reviewed the genera Pseudamnicola and Mercuria, and placed this species within Pseudamnicola.
The generic position is uncertain in absence of anatomical data. Synonymisation based on Boeters (1976).
This species is currently placed as taxon inquirendum by MolluscaBase (2022).

The genus Marstonia was formerly relegated to the synonomy of Pyrgulopsis by Hershler and Thompson (1987), but Thompson and Hershler (2002) later re-evaluated eastern North American species assigned to Pyrgulopsis and recognized them as distinct species of the genus Marstonia.

This species was considered a synonym of Plethodon mississippi by Himes and Beckett (2013). It was tentatively resurrected from this synonymy by Pierson et al. (2020). This species is currently recognized as valid, although further taxonomic work is recommended.

In the 1996 Red List this was mistakenly entered as Pseudocampylaea spurca, instead of Pseudohelenoconcha spurca. P. dianae, P. laetissima and P. persoluta were also entered incorrectly, plus these should have been placed into synonymy under Pseudohelenoconcha spurca.

In the 1996 Red List this was incorrectly listed as Tornigenus gibberulus ssp. Digerus. The generic name was misspelt and the ssp. given was in fact the subgeneric name. It is still considered a valid species.
In the 1996 Red List this was incorrectly listed as Tornigenus turbinatus ssp. Biolocus. The generic name was misspelt and the ssp. given was in fact the subgeneric name.
There is some doubt as to its taxonomic status.
Descrita em: Eichler, A., 1870. Videnskabelige Meddelelser fra Dansk Naturhistorisk Forening i Kjøbenhavn 1870: 206.Popularmente conhecida por bapeba veludo (Lima, 2017).

Descrita em: Candollea 9: 390, 1942. É reconhecida pelas folhas estreitas e lineares, muitas vezes mais longas do que largas (Pennington, 1990). A espécie foi avaliada como Extinta (EX) na Lista Vermelha da IUCN (Pires O'Brien, J., 1998).
Also treated under the genus Goniobasis.
Note correction to scientific spelling of Pantagenia to Pentagenia.
Genus and author names were incorrectly spelled as "Megalolulimus" and "Moiretes" in 1996 and 2000 Red Lists.
Initially described as Perionychella (Vesiculodrilus) pedderensis by Jamieson (1974). Taxonomy revised by Blakenmore in 1996.

The genus Vanvoorstia contains three species. Vanvoorstia spectabilis and V. coccinea are common tropical (Indo-Pacific, including GBR) species, with the former also recorded from Lord Howe Island. While some confusion exists as to the exact differences between these two species (Price and Scott 1992), both are easily distinguished and considered very different from V. bennettiana, a very much smaller- and finer-meshed species in which the tetrasporangial stichidia are also easily defined.

There are now four species. Eric Coppejans (pers. comm.) indicates that there is a new species he described from East Africa which is probably Critically Endangered: Vanvoorstia incipiens De Clerck, Wynne & Coppejans (Phycologia 38 (1999): 394-400). This newly described species occurs massively in a single (rather small) bay along the east coast of Zanzibar, at about low tide level (large amounts drifting or entangled to other seaweeds in intertidal pools). Coppejans carried out over 200 collecting excursions along the Kenyan, Tanzanian (incl. Zanzibar) coast and NEVER found a single specimen anywhere else than the type locality, where we find it again year after year. It doesn't occur in the neighbouring bays, which look "identical" to this one! If that bay would be disturbed (harbour, oil pollution, etc.) the only known (type) locality would disappear and we would have a similar story there within the same genus!! Apparently some representatives do not succeed in colonizing larger areas!
Treated by some as a variety under A. splendens (Achyranthes splendens var. atollensis (H. St. John) Govaerts) see World Checklist of Seed Plants 1(1): 6. 1995.

Synonym: Cyanea grimesiana ssp. cylindrocalyx.

Information from NatureServe (2003): "Treated as Cyanea grimesiana ssp. cylindrocalyx in the Hawaii Manual (Wagner et al., 1990); recognized as the species Cyanea cylindrocalyx in the Manual's Supplement (Wagner and Herbst, 1999) and by Kartesz (1999 Synthesis)".

Eschmeyer notes that this species was regarded as a synonym of Coregonus zenithicus by Lee et al. (1980), but was then recognised as a valid species by Smith (1985) and by Scott and Crossman (1998). However, FishBase list C. alpenae as a synonym of C. zenithicus following Page and Burr (1991).
There is considerable doubt as to whether this is a valid taxon, and some authors argue that it is just a form of Coregonus artedi.

This species' taxonomy has been the subject of controversy with a number of studies suggesting it remains extant, although molecular studies (e.g., Hansen et al., 2008; Jacobsen et al., 2012) have failed to rule out that the extinct North Sea Coregonus populations were polyphyletic. The name C. oxyrhynchus continues to be misapplied to whitefishes (C. maraena) inhabiting rivers draining into the eastern North Sea in Germany and Denmark (e.g., Jepsen et al., 2012; Jensen et al., 2015).
The 1996 and 2000 IUCN Red Lists included C. borbonica as a separate species, this is now placed as a synonym of C. indica.
Was previously included in T. simonis, but is valid as a separate species (N. Bogutskaya, pers. comm.).
Also treated under the genus Goniobasis.
Was listed in the 1996 IUCN Red List under the name Dysnomia arcaeformis?.
Was listed in the 1996 IUCN Red List under the name Dysnomia biemarginata?.
Was listed in the 1996 IUCN Red List under the name Dysnomia flexuosa.
Was listed in the 1996 IUCN Red List under the name Dysnomia haysiana.
Was listed in the 1996 IUCN Red List under the name Dysnomia lenior.

This species was historically placed in the genera Dysnomia and Plagiola (Johnson 1978) and is now placed in genus Epioblasma (Williams et al. 2008).

A list of synonyms for this species can be found on The MUSSEL project web site (Graf and Cummings 2011).

This species was historically placed in the genera Dysnomia and Plagiola (Johnson 1978). This species is currently place in the genus Epioblasma (Williams et al. 2008).

A list of synonyms for this species can be found on The MUSSEL project web site (Graf and Cummings 2011).
Was listed in the 1996 IUCN Red List under the name Dysnomia sampsoni.
Was listed in the 1996 IUCN Red List under the name Dysnomia lewisii?.
Was listed in the 1996 IUCN Red List under the name Dysnomia stewardsoni.

The extinct Quagga is now considered to be a subspecies of the Plains Zebra based mainly on genetic evidence (e.g. Higuchi et al. 1984, Leonard et al. 2005; although see Bennett 1980, Klein and Cruz-Uribe 1999).

The current spelling of the specific name is correct. Clarke's (1985) spelling change, Alasmidonta maccordi, was unjustified and constituted a recommendation only (Turgeon et al. 1998).

A list of synonyms for this species can be found on The MUSSEL project web site (Graf and Cummings 2011).
The identity of this species is uncertain, the four specimens collected may be immature. Its generic placement is questionable.

Three species of Palaeopropithecus have been described (P. ingens, P. maximus, and P. kelyus).  Palaeopropithecus kelyus is clearly distinct from the other two; differences between P. ingens and P. maximus are small, and they may represent geographic variants of the same species.

Previously included in its own monotypic family (Xenothricidae, Hershkovitz 1970, MacPhee and Fleagle 1991), current morphological and molecular evidence indicate that this species is closely related to members of tribe Callitrichini in the family Pitheciidae (MacPhee and Horovitz 2004, Woods et al. 2018).
The population from Lake Salda is usually identified as this species. This is very likely to be incorrect and the assessment is therefore restricted to the population of Lake Gölçük only.
Generic name changed from Phoxinellus to Pseudophoxinus, based on information in Eschmeyer (1998) and recommendation of Kottelat (pers. comm. 2001).
Following Eschmeyer (2004) Lagochila lacera was transferred to Moxostoma lacerum.

Originally described as a full species, this taxon was downgraded to a subspecies of L. riparia by Kirby (1904). The taxon was reinstated as a valid species by Brindle (1970) and synonymised with L. loveridgei Zeuner, 1962 which had been described from subfossil forceps.
No subspecies are recognised.
No subspecies have been described.
No subspecies have been described.

No subspecies are recognised.

No subspecies are recognised. Perameles eremiana was closely related to P. bougainville and it has been proposed that they are clinal forms of the same species (Friedman 1967); however, Westerman et al. (2012) recommended maintaining them as separate species and we have followed this recommendation.
No subspecies are recognised.

McKean (1975) described the species from a single skull found in a shallow cave, and provisionally placed it within the genus Nyctophilus. While the generic assignment remains uncertain (Parnaby 2009, Jackson and Groves 2015) the species status appears to be unchallenged.

The taxonomic status of this species is unclear (Mickleburgh et al. 1992). Conder (2008) states that the species is distinct from all other Australian Pteropus species, but there has been speculation that the single specimen might in fact be a vagrant of another species. Despite much survey effort, the species has not been found on the Percy Islands recently. Koopman (1984) discusses the uncertain taxonomic status of P. brunneus at length due to how distinct it is from other known Pteropus in the region. More taxonomic work is needed.
Díaz et al. (2002) described Gracilinanus ignitus as a new species. Voss et al. (2005) described a new genus, Cryptonanus, and transferred G. ignitus to this new genus.
Was previously considered a subspecies of Geocapromys brownii.

According to Woods in Wilson and reeder (1993) columbianus is only know from Holocene fossils from Cuba and may be from the genus Capromys. G. Amori (pers. comm. 2001) advises retaining this species, agreeing with MacPhee and Flemming (1999).
Plagiodontia velozi was listed in 1996 as Extinct is considered to be a synonym of P. ipnaeum (see Novak 1999, Woods in Wilson and Reeder 1993).
This species includes the junior synonym H. antillensis which was previously interpreted as a separate species.
This species was previously removed from The IUCN Red List because it was considered to have become extinct before 1500 AD. However, it is now known to have survived into modern times.
Will be transferred to family Cricetidae.
Will be transferred to family Cricetidae.
This is often regarded as a synonym or subspecies of the mainland Oryzomys couesi (Wilson and Reeder 2005). Following Weksler et al. (2006), it is maintained here as a valid species.
Will be transferred to family Cricetidae.

This species previously has been considered a synonymous with Nesoryzomys narboroughi (see Musser and Carleton 1993). Recent evidence suggests that the two should be treated as separate species (Dowler et al. 2000). More research is needed to confirm that these are really two different species (M. Weksler pers. comm).
No subspecies are recognised.
No subspecies are recognised. Mahoney (1977) found that the single skull was distinct from other Notomys and that it was likely to be most closely related to Mitchell’s Hopping-mouse N. mitchellii.

Coryphomys buehleri is one of four species, each in its own genus, of giant rats (three have yet to be named and described) endemic to Timor; all are known only by subfossils (Glover 1986) and may be related to the New Guinea Old Endemics placed in the Pogonomys Group (Musser and Carleton 2005).

Recent evidence suggests that this may not represent a unique taxon (C. Groves pers. comm. 2008; and see Robins et al. 2006, Galbraeth 2007). It seems fairly evident now that Sus bucculentus is not a valid taxon. It is not, however, a synonym of Sus scrofa, but of Sus moupinensis (Groves and Grubb 2011). The latter species remains provisional, however, awaiting further study of taxonomic differentiation within the ‘scrofic’ group of pigs. What remains unclear is whether a verrucosic-type pig species existed in the Annamite Mountains area that hybridized with a 'scrofic' type species (scrofa or moupinensis) to the point that it is no longer morphologically distinct. Alternatively, there was never a distinct taxon. Pending further study, Sus bucculentus is classified as Extinct until better evidence regarding its taxonomy becomes available.

Sea Mink has been regarded as a subspecies of the American Mink Neovison vison, but Mead et al. (2000) and Wozencraft (2005) recognized it as a distinct species. Both are commonly included in Mustela, but were separated into Neovison according to Abramov (2000). Cytogenetic and biochemical data support their placement in the genus Neovison (Wozencraft 2005).

Grandidier (1902) described a large form of Cryptoprocta ferox from subfossil material dating from the presumed Holocene in Madagascar that he referred to the variety spelea. Subsequently, there has been varying opinion on the validity of this taxon. Goodman et al. (2004) examined and analysed 159 subfossil and 32 modern osteological specimens of Cryptoprocta and concluded that this was a valid species that existed on Madagascar in the recent geological past.

The genus Monachus previously included three geographically widely separated species: the Mediterranean Monk Seal, Monachus monachus; the Caribbean Monk Seal, Monachus tropicalis; and the Hawaiian Monk Seal, Monachus schauinslandi (Rice 1998).  Recent studies  (Scheel et al. 2014) have shown that molecular, morphological, and temporal divergence between the Mediterranean and New World Monk Seals (Hawaiian and Caribbean) is equivalent to or greater than between sister genera of other phocids. As a result, Caribbean and Hawaiian Monk Seals have been reclassified together in a newly erected genus, Neomonachus. Considered the most primitive of all living phocid species, monk seals have anatomical features that resemble those of seal fossils from 14-16 million years ago (Barnes et al. 1985).

See Taxonomic Notes for the species. Moodley et al.'s (2017) study also found that the historic range of the Western Black Rhino (Diceros bicornis longipes) that has been declared Extinct extends into an inter-crossed predominantly D. b. michaeli subpopulation in the Masai Mara (CV haplogroup). However, very few individuals with this CV haplotype probably survive.

Barbus microbarbis is doubtful as valid species. It is possibly a hybrid of a Barbus species and a Varicorhinus species (Banister 1973, De Vos and Thys van den Audenaerde 1990, De Vos et al. 1990, De Vos et al. 2001).

The nominate subspecies, the Bubal Hartebeest (A. b. buselaphus) is one of eight subspecies of Hartebeest, following Gosling and Capellini (2013). The others being: Western Hartebeest or Kanki (A. b. major); Lelwel Hartebeest (A. b. lelwel); Tora Hartebeest (A. b. tora); Swayne's Hartebeest or Korkay (A. b. swaynei); Coke's Hartebeest or Kongoni (A. b. cokii); Lichtenstein's Hartebeest (A. b. lichtensteinii); and Red Hartebeest (A. b. caama).

Gazella saudiya is sometimes treated as a subspecies of Gazella dorcas but, on the basis of genetic analyses, Hammond et al. (2001) maintained that G. saudiya was distinct from G. dorcas, though closely related to it. See also Groves (1988) and Grubb (2005).

The validity of this taxon is unclear. Some authors have considered bilkis as a subspecies of G. arabica, a little-known gazelle known from a few specimens on the Farasan Islands (Groves 1996, Grubb 2005). However, the type specimen of G. arabica has recently been shown by DNA analysis to be a misidentified specimen of G. gazella (Bärman et al. 2012). Genetic research at King Khaled Wildlife Research Centre, Saudi Arabia, also raised some doubts about the validity of the specific status of G. bilkis. Regardless, there is no doubt that the population of gazelles originally described as G. bilkis is certainly now extinct.

Robert's Lechwe (Kobus leche robertsi) is one of five subspecies of Southern Lechwe (Kobus leche), following Ansell and Banfield (1979), Birungi and Arctander (2001) and Cotterill (2005). The other subspecies being: Black Lechwe (K. l. smithemani); Kafue Lechwe (K. l. kafuensis); Red Lechwe (K. l. leche) and Upemba Lechwe (K. l. anselli).

Morphological analyses support the view that Lithobates fisheri represents a distinct species (Jennings et al. 1995). Subpopulations from central Arizona and western New Mexico previously attributed to L. chiricahuensis have been suggested to belong to species on the basis of mtDNA analysis (Hekkala et al. 2011), however, this claim is disputed and is currently not recognized (Herrman et al. 2021).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).

This species was previously within the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005). There is some doubt as to the correctness of the locality data associated with the specimen and there might also be taxonomic problems with this species (J. Savage pers. comm.).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
The placement of Pantanodon is problematic. Based on the most recent studies, it should be placed under Poeciliidae (Parenti 1981, Ghedotti 2000) (J. Sparks pers. comm.)
This species was formally described in 2006 based on specimens held at MNHN, Paris (Stiassny and Sparks 2006).

This species was treated by Robinson in Jørgensen & León-Yanez (1999) as a synonym of D. repens, D. atripliciformis like. An examination of the type material of these taxa reveals that this treatment is not correct (A. Tye pers. obs., N. Hinde. pers. comm.). The type of D. atripliciformis is obviously a specimen of D. biflora. There are tree specimens of D. inelegans, which are part of a single collection made by Charles Darwin; two of them are very small and in poor condition, but the third is an excellent specimen of a complete plant. The material shows that D. inelegans is genuine and that it is very different to D. biflora and D. repens. D. inelegans is a large plant with erect growth habit (with the base of sufrutescente stem) and leaves that reach up to five centimetres long and four wide. The inflorescence and flower structure of D. inelegans are also very different from the other two species: D. inelegans has large, complex groups, while D. repens has simple florets with few flowers. The structure of the female flowers is also very different. Thus there are three distinct taxa Delilia species in the Galapagos: biflora, inelegans and repens.

Contomastix charrua was described from a population referred to Cnemidophorus (now Contomastix) lacertoides on the basis of differences in coloration, structure of the hyoid apparatus and geological history of the cape (Cabrera and Carreira 2009). Borteiro et al.(2013) found no morphological differences between the two taxa and referred C. charrua to the synonymy of C. lacertoides. S. Carreira (pers. comm. 2016) indicates that ongoing research has identified additional differences that may warrant recognizing C. charrua as a separate species, and recommends retaining C. charrua as a valid species pending comparison with material from the C. lacertoides type locality, which was not done by Borteiro et al. (2013).

The existence of two distinct ‘ebony’ species on St Helena was not recognized until clearly demonstrated by Quentin Cronk in 1995. A sister species, the Dwarf Ebony (T. ebenus Cronk), was rediscovered in 1980 and for several years was erroneously assumed to be the same taxon as that described in 18th Century literature. Confusion persist to this day, but the densely silvered leaves and much smaller flowers of T. melanoxylon are very distinctive.

It is unclear whether this species truly belongs in Heliotropium or in Tournefourtia, as the only available collection is inconclusive. The critical distinction between the two genera lies in the morphology of the fruits, of which there is no surviving sample.

Originally described as a subspecies of B. penicillata (Finlayson 1957), the Desert Bettong has only recently been recognized as a full species (McDowell et al. 2015). Finlayson (1958) provided a more detailed description of the skull and speculated that it represented a full species. However, Wakefield (1967) later synonymised anhydra with B. lesueur, based on his opinion that several features of the skull were similar to B. lesueur, although he noted that ‘the skull is very small’ (Wakefield 1967, p. 11). The Desert Bettong can be separated from the Woylie B. penicillata and the Boodie B. lesueur by several skull and dentition characters (McDowell 2013). Ancient DNA (aDNA) analysis of the Cytochrome b gene from the holotype shows it is a well-supported lineage, distinct enough from its closest relatives B. penicillata and B. lesueur to consider it a separate species (McDowell et al. 2015).
No subspecies are recognized.
Recent taxonomic work by Liew Thorseng has shown that this species is part of the genus Plectostoma.

We depart from the taxonomy of Pelodryadidae proposed by Dubois and Frétey (2016) and Duellman et al. (2016) and retain the composition of Litoria, Nyctimystes and Cyclorana as previously recognised. This taxonomy is currently used in all Australian lists (e.g., ASH list, State and Federal government lists) and field guides (e.g., Hoskin et al. 2015, Cogger 2018, Clulow and Swan 2018).

Giles (1937) stressed the close taxonomic relationship of this deer with R. duvaucelii, within which it was placed by Haltenorth (1963: 58), Groves (1982; tentatively) and Corbet and Hill (1992). It was considered a full species by Pocock (1943), who even assigned it to its own monotypic genus Thaocervus, and by Lekagul and McNeely (1977), Groves and Grubb (1987) and Pitra et al. (2004). Most sources during 1945 to 2015 placed the species in the genus Cervus.
This species is the sister taxon of the also extinct, but insular, Falklands Wolf (Dusicyon australis).

Örstan (2014) reported three individuals (one mature and two juvenile) from the Karaburun peninsula on the Turkish coast opposite Chios Island, and tentatively identified them as Vitrea storchi. The specimens are considered here as V. aff. storchi (M. Seddon pers. comm. 2017). The identity of these records requires confirmation.
This species is considered endemic to Java, and previous records of this  species from throughout the rest of Southeast Asia refer to other  species (Kottelat and Widjanarti 2005).

Two dwarfed hippopotami were described from recent fossil remains at Madagascar: Hippopotamus lemerlei and Hippopotamus madagascariensis. In a critical contribution, Stuenes (1989) thoroughly described the morphological differences between these species and provided detailed diagnoses. After Stuenes’ work (1989), the most complete account is that by Rakotovao et al. (2014), who notably documented significant intraspecific variations within both species. The origin of these species remains uncertain: they are generally seen as deriving from continental species of Hippopotamus, maybe from the extant Hippopotamus amphibius. A third extinct Madagascan species, Hippopotamus laloumena, was proposed by Faure and Guérin (1990) on limited evidence. A recent publication by Faure et al. (2010) does not add significant evidence in favor of the validity of this species, and  its dissimilarity from Hippopotamus amphibius needs to be clarified. It may represent evidence for sporadic Mozambique Channel crossing by individuals of the extant large species during the Holocene, including since the European colonization of Madagascar (Burney et al. 2004).

Fovet et al. (2011) suggested that Guldberg's type specimen of H. madagscariensis actually pertains to the other small species, H. lemerlei. In 1902, C.J.F. Major re-described H. madagascariensis Gulberg, 1883 using a new Malagasy skeleton which was quite different to H. lemerlei. However, because H. madagascariensis would be no more than a replacement name for H. lemerlei, Fovet et al. (2011) proposed the new name H. guldbergi to designate the species described in 1902 by C.J.F. Major. Rakotovao et al. (2014) disagreed with Fauvet et al. (2011) on the attribution of Guldberg’s specimen to H. lemerlei, and confirmed its identification as H. madagascariensis, in line with Stuenes (1989). This debate is not closed (see Faure et al. 2015), but given that H. madagascariensis was extensively used as an available name prior to 1961 and since then (see section 11.6 of the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature), and given that the ICZN recommendations regarding the stability of taxonomic nomenclature, it is for now more cautious to continue to use H. madagascariensis and to consider H. guldbergi as its junior synonym. In any case, this debate calls for further revising the material attributed to the two dwarfed hippopotami from Madagascar, including notably their postcranial skeleton.

Two dwarfed hippopotami were created from recent fossil remains in Madagascar: Hippopotamus lemerlei and Hippopotamus madagascariensis. In a critical contribution, Stuenes (1989) thoroughly described the morphological differences between these species and provided detailed diagnoses. After Stuenes' work (1989), the most complete account is that by Rakotovao et al. (2014), who notably documented significant intraspecific variations within both species. The origin of these species remains uncertain: they are generally seen as deriving from continental species of Hippopotamus, maybe from Hippopotamus amphibius. A third extinct Madagascan species, Hippopotamus laloumena, was proposed by Faure and Guérin (1990) on limited evidence. A recent publication by Faure et al. (2010) does not add significant evidence in favor of the validity of this species, and its dissimilarity from Hippopotamus amphibius still needs to be clarified (Weston and Lister 2009). It may represent evidence for sporadic Mozambique Channel crossing by individuals of the extant large species during the Holocene, including since the European colonization of Madagascar (Burney et al. 2004).

Fovet et al. (2011) suggested that Guldberg's type specimen of H. madagscariensis actually pertains to the other small species, H. lemmerlei. In 1902, C.J.F. Major re-described H. madagascariensis Gulberg, 1883 using a new Malagasy skeleton which was quite different to H. lemmerlei. However, because H. madagscariensis would be no more than a replacement name for H. lemerlei, Fovet et al. (2011) proposed the new name H. guldbergi to designate the species described in 1902 by C.J.F. Major. Rakotovao et al. (2014) disagreed with Fauvet et al. (2011) on the attribution of Guldberg’s specimen to H. lemerlei, and confirmed its identification as H. madagascariensis, in line with Stuenes (1989). This debate is not closed (see Faure et al. 2015), but given that H. madagascariensis was extensively used as an available name prior to 1961 and since then (see section 11.6 of the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature), and given that the ICZN recommendations regarding the stability of taxonomic nomenclature, it is for now more cautious to continue to use H. madagascariensis and to consider H. gulbergi as its junior synonym. In any case, this debate calls for further revising the material attributed to the two dwarfed hippopotami from Madagascar, including notably their postcranial skeleton.

The genus name Germainaia was created by Graf & Cummings (2009) for a few medium sized najad shells that had been collected by the French naturalist Martin-François Geay during his explorations in Madagascar (1904-1908) and originally described as Unio (Nodularia) geayi by Germain (2011). No precise type locality is known and considering that Geay also collected in New Zealand and Australia in 1908, where he died, the origin of the material remains uncertain. Graf and Cummings (2009, 2011) do accept that the material originates from Madagascar, adding that its family classification remains doubtful (incertae sedis), i.e. either Unionidae (with Laurasian and African distribution) or Hyriidae (Australian- S. American).

Unio madagascariensis is a nomen dubium (Graf & Cummings, 2009). It is only known from the extremely summary description of  Sganzin (1841) who states that adult specimens have the size of a Potadoma littoralis (hence with an adult lenght of ca. 50-70 mm) but are very fragile and of a greenish color.

Unio malgachensis is also considered a nomen dubium by Graf & Cummings (2009). Only the type is known, which is of a juvenile najad (L = 12 mm) that can not be identified on genus or family level (Graf and Cummings 2009).
Monotypic.
Occasionally regarded as conspecific with globally threatened N. meridionalis of New Zealand. N. norfolcensis is a synonym. Monotypic.
Psephotellus pulcherrimus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Psephotus.
Mascarinus mascarin (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously listed as M. mascarinus.

Palaeornis wardi (Handbook of the Birds of the World and BirdLife International 2020) was previously listed as Psittacula wardi (del Hoyo et al. 2014). Braun et al. (2019) report the situation where the parrot genera Psittinus, Tanygnathus and Mascarinus nest genetically within Psittacula, meaning that either Psittacula replaces these latter three genera or it breaks down into monophyletic genera of their own. The latter course is preferred, building on Braun et al. (2016), where several genera were established or resurrected including Palaeornis for P. eupatria and P. wardi.

Alexandrinus exsul (Handbook of the Birds of the World and BirdLife International 2020) was previously listed as Psittacula exsul (del Hoyo et al. 2014). Braun et al. (2019) report the situation where the parrot genera Psittinus, Tanygnathus and Mascarinus nest genetically within Psittacula, meaning that either Psittacula replaces these latter three genera or it breaks down into monophyletic genera of their own. The latter course is preferred, building on Braun et al. (2016), where several genera were established, including Alexandrinus for P. krameri, P. eques and P. exsul.

Previously placed in monotypic genus Sceloglaux but moved to Ninox following Wood et al. (2017) and Salter et al. (2020). Geographical variation questionable, and size differences perhaps clinal; rufifacies sometimes synonymized with albifacies. Two subspecies tentatively recognized.

Previously (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) placed in the genus Alopecoenas (as A. ferrugineus) and before that in the genus Gallicolumba but transferred to Pampusana on the grounds of the latter’s priority (Bruce et al. 2016). Name sometimes attributed to J. R. Forster, but although his description was written in 1775, and served as basis for Wagler (as acknowledged by Wagler himself [Wagler 1829]), Forster’s notes were first formally published 56 years posthumously, in 1844. Monotypic.

Previously (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) placed in the genus Alopecoenas and before that in the genus Gallicolumba but transferred to Pampusana on the grounds of the latter’s priority (Bruce et al. 2016). Closely allied to P. sanctaecrucis and (especially) P. stairi, and more distantly so to the P. jobiensis group. Monotypic.
Alectroenas nitidissimus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously listed as A. nitidissima.
Hypotaenidia wakensis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Gallirallus. Monotypic.

Hypotaenidia pacifica (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Gallirallus as G. pacificus.

The name ecaudatus or ecaudata, often incorrectly used for this species, in fact refers to Buff-banded Rail H. philippensis (Taylor 1998).
Hypotaenidia dieffenbachii (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Gallirallus.
Zapornia palmeri (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Porzana.

Zapornia sandwichensis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Porzana.

Porzana millsi (often incorrectly spelled "millei") is a synonym, used for the darker, probably immature, form of the species (Taylor 1998).
Zapornia monasa (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Porzana.

Provisionally treated within genus Urile based on morphological similarities between this species and the other three species recently assigned therein following Kennedy and Spencer (2014); however this extinct taxon was not included in the molecular sampling.
Viridonia sagittirostris (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Hemignathus following AOU (1998 & supplements); Brooks (2000); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).
Coenocorypha aucklandica, C. huegeli, C. barrierensis and C. iredalei (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as C. aucklandica following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Dromaius minor (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously listed as D. ater following Christidis and Boles (1994); the name minor has priority.
Alopochen mauritiana (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously listed as A. mauritianus.
Monotypic.
Porphyrio caerulescens (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously listed as P. coerulescens.
Hypotaenidia poeciloptera (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Nesoclopeus as N. poecilopterus.

Saint Helena Crake Laterallus podarces (Handbook of the Birds of the World and BirdLife International 2020) was previously in the genus Atlantisia (del Hoyo et al. 2014) owing to similarities with Inaccessible Rail, for which that genus was created. Stervander et al. (2019) found that Inaccessible Rail actually nests within a clade of Laterallus crakes, grouped closely with Black Rail Laterallus jamaicensis, and it has therefore been placed in the genus Laterallus. As the assignment of Saint Helena Crake to Atlantisia was based upon similarity to Inaccessible Rail, it is logical to also move the extinct taxon into Laterallus, despite the taxon not being assessed in Stervander et al. (2019).
Zapornia nigra (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Porzana.
Zapornia astrictocarpus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Porzana. Monotypic.

Gallinula nesiotis and G. comeri (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as G. nesiotis following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993) and Groenenburg et al. (2008, 2009), and before that had been treated as separate species by Collar and Stuart (1985).
Fulica newtonii (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously listed as F. newtoni.
Sometimes placed in genus Pseudobulweria. Monotypic.
Monotypic.

Often treated as a subspecies of A. melanura of mainland New Zealand and other islands, but differed in larger size of male, greater extent of blue on the head, less yellow in plumage overall and no yellow flank patch, and in having a yellow, not a dark, eye. Monotypic.
Monotypic.
Necropsittacus rodricanus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously listed as N. rodericanus.
Sometimes placed in genus Gallirallus or Rallus. Monotypic.
Erythromachus leguati (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Aphanapteryx.

Poodytes rufescens (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously listed as Bowdleria rufescens. Usually considered a subspecies of P. punctatus, but sometimes treated as separate species (perhaps more closely related to Fijian Cincloramphus rufus). Differed from P. punctatus in its white vs brown-streaked grey chin to lower belly (4); strong rufescent tone of upperparts, wings, tail and flanks (2); bolder, blacker streaks on upperparts and flanks (2); and osteological features (Olson 1990b). Close in size to P. caudatus, which was previously also treated as a subspecies of P. punctatus. Monotypic.
Coenocorypha aucklandica, C. huegeli, C. barrierensis and C. iredalei (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as C. aucklandica following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Commidendrum forms a monophyletic endemic genus with no very close affinities (Noyes and Reiseberg 1999).

The Gumwood (Commidendrum robustum (Roxb.) DC.) was split into two subspecies by Cronk (2000):
  • subsp. robustum; all extant plants belong to this taxon.
  • subsp. gummiferum Cronk; this taxon was provisionally ascribed to confusing 19th Century specimens of uncertain identity, which had been formerly classified as C. gummiferum (Roxb.) DC.

Some of the specimens labelled as C. gummiferum lie within the range of variation exhibited by C. robustum subsp. robustum. The remainder certainly belong to a distinct taxon, but their classification as a subspecies is difficult to reconcile with the fundamental differences in flower and inflorescence structure from subsp. robustum. In fact, they are somewhat closer to the False Gumwood (C. spurium (G.Forst) DC.). For this reason, the current treatment restores C. gummiferum as a species, though uncertainties persist over its true position, and there is a strong possibility that it may be a hybrid between the two surviving parents.

The well-defined C. robustum is thus retained as a species concept without division at subspecific level. Subspecies gummiferumhas been promoted to species level under C. gummiferum, along with the Red List assessment done by Q. Cronk in 1998.
Brock (1999) placed the species in the monospecific genus of Pseudobactricia of which it is the type species.

The taxonomy of this species has been disputed over the years. It was reclassified as Partula jackieburchi and then as Partula otaheitana rubescens by Johnson, Murray and Clarke (1986). Gerlach (2016) placed it in Partula.

Michaelsen's contemporary, Ude (1905) thought his species Notoscolex unipapillatus may be the same as T. orthostichon but this was disputed by Blakemore (2012) and by current studies (Blakemore, unpublished).  Of note is that the revision based on types by Michaelsen (1917) did not mention this similarity and showed the male pores to be radically different, both to M. unipapillatus and to Lee’s (1962) revision of London specimens of “Megascolides orthostichon” that Blakemore (2014) showed was T. maorica (see Blakemore 2014 fig. 12 comparisons with Benham’s original figures).  Lee (1962) was seemingly unaware of Michaelsen’s (1917) revision and also missed his own (Lee 1959) review as another apparently significant difference is the spermathecal pores being segmental in T. maorica rather than intersegmental as in T. unipapillata.  For T. orthostichon the spermathecal pore location was given by Lee (1959) as in 7/8/9 the same as T. unipapillatus but – as already noted – Michaelsen (1917) found the male pores and markings, at least, to differ conclusively for these two taxa.

Hypogaeon orthostichon Schmarda (1861) was the first native earthworm formally described from Australasia.  It was collected from Maunga Rei / Mount Wellington in Auckland, New Zealand by Ludwig Karl Schmarda sometime over a five week period of his visit in 1854.
This species was reviewed by Benham (1905), Michaelsen (1917), Lee (1959) and Blakemore (2000, 2008, 2012) with new combination in Tokea by Blakemore (2014).
Although the description of Tokea orthostichon (Schmarda, 1861) was basic, and partly in Latin, it was standard orthodoxy for the time and quite adequate for this species that Schmarda collected at Maunga Rei / Mount Wellington in 1854 as part of a world tour.
Carpodacus ferreorostris (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Chaunoproctus following Brooks (2000); Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

The Japanese Sea Lion has sometimes been considered a subspecies of Zalophus californianus, Z. c. japonicus. Rice (1998) argued for the retention of Z. californianus, Z. japonicus, and Z. wollebaeki as distinct species without providing new evidence. From studies of skull morphology Brunner (2003) argued for species status for these three taxa. In addition, Sakahira and Niimi (2007) and Wolf et al. (2007) provide genetic evidence that Z. japonicus is best considered a separate species.

Persoonia prostrata is very similar to specimens of P. stradbrokensis collected from the mainland south of Fraser Island, but differs in its prostrate habit, usually smaller leaves and smaller flowers. These differences are based on only two collections for P. prostrata, neither of which is an adequate specimen. It may be that P. prostrata and P. stradbrokensis are conspecific, and that P. prostrata is just a prostrate, maritime form. However, the distributions of these species are separated by over 100 km.
Loxops coccineus, L. ochraceus and L. wolstenholmei (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as L. coccineus following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).
Acrocephalus caffer, A. musae and A. longirostris (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as A. caffer following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Zosterops conspicillatus and Z. saypani (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as Z. conspicillatus following Slikas et al. (2000).
Chenonetta finschi (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) is recognised following evidence presented in Holdaway et al. (2002).
Columba thiriouxi (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was newly described from subfossil records by Hume (2011).
Nesoenas cicur (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was newly described from subfossil records by Hume (2011).
Nesoenas rodericanus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Alectroenas.
Alectroenas payandeei (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was described from subfossil remains by Hume (2011).
Dryolimnas augusti (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was described from fossils by Mourer-Chauviré et al. (1999).
Porphyrio paepae (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was described by Steadman (1988) from bones found at two archaeological sites.
Tribonyx hodgenorum (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was shown by Cassels et al. (1988) to have persisted into the 17th century.
Nyctanassa carcinocatactes (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was newly-described from fossil remains by Olson and Wingate (2006).
Prosobonia cancellata and P. parvirostris (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as P. cancellata following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Eclectus infectus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was newly-described from subfossil remains by Steadman (2006).

Pyrocephalus rubinus, P. nanus and P. dubius (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as P. rubinus following AOU (1998 & supplements), SACC (2005 & updates), Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993) and Stotz et al. (1996).
Aplonis ulietensis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) is recognised as a species following the work of Hume and Walters (2012).

Nesoenas duboisi (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Columba.

There were probably two other native pigeons on the island-a slaty, blue-winged Alectroenas, and unidentified ramiers. All three apparently became extinct in the early 1700s (Cheke 1987). Adler (1994) confused the situation by applying the name duboisi to the (undescribed) Alectroenas. Archeological work is needed to clarify the situation.
Acrocephalus luscinius, A. hiwae, A. yamashinae, A. astrolabii and A. nijoi (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as A. luscinius following Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).
Acrocephalus luscinius, A. hiwae, A. yamashinae, A. astrolabii and A. nijoi (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as A. luscinius following Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).
Acrocephalus luscinius, A. hiwae, A. yamashinae, A. astrolabii and A. nijoi (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as A. luscinius following Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).
Akialoa ellisiana, A. stejnegeri and A. lanaiensis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously placed in the genus Hemignathus and lumped as H. ellisianus following AOU (1998 and supplements).
Akialoa ellisiana, A. stejnegeri and A. lanaiensis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously placed in the genus Hemignathus and lumped as H. ellisianus following AOU (1998 and supplements).
Akialoa obscura (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Hemignathus and listed as H. obscurus following AOU (1998 & supplements); Brooks (2000).
Akialoa ellisiana, A. stejnegeri and A. lanaiensis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously placed in the genus Hemignathus and lumped as H. ellisianus following AOU (1998 and supplements).
Foudia delloni (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was described by Cheke and Hume (2008).
Himatione sanguinea and H. fraithii (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as H. sanguinea following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).

Zosterops maderaspatanus , Z. kirki and Z. semiflavus (del Hoyo and Collar   2016) were previously lumped as Z. maderaspatanus following Dowsett & Forbes-Watson (1993) and Sibley &   Monroe (1990, 1993).
Acrocephalus luscinius, A. hiwae, A. yamashinae, A. astrolabii and A. nijoi (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as A. luscinius following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
No subspecies are recognised
Tsigenopoulos et al. (2010) transferred 'Barbus' reinii to the genus Labeobarbus.
Levin et al. (2012) transferred this species to the genus Luciobarbus.

This is the new concept of Luciobarbus nasus, following a systematic review by Doadrio et al. (2016) with the old concept having been divided into four species: Luciobarbus magniatlantis, Luciobarbus guercifensis, Luciobarbus zayanensis, and this new restricted concept of Luciobarbus nasus, each of which are now assessed separately.

Five endemic Salmo populations from northwest Africa are currently recognised as valid species. All are members of the so-called 'Salmo trutta' (brown trout) complex', which is widely distributed across much of the Palearctic region. However, taxonomic classification within this complex remains a matter of discussion due to its complicated evolutionary history and inherent phenotypic diversity. While a consensus regarding the existence of several distinct phylogeographic lineages (Atlantic, Duero, Mediterranean, Adriatic, Marmoratus, Danubian and Tigris) has been reached, the evolutionary relationships between them remain unclear. In northwest Africa, mitochondrial and nuclear DNA analyses have revealed the existence of three major clades which derived from multiple waves of ancient colonisation; (1) an Afro-Atlantic clade inhabiting Mediterranean coastal rivers of North Africa and the Sous River system in Atlantic Morocco, stemming from a colonisation wave of the Atlantic lineage from Iberia, (2) a relict and native clade inhabiting the Draa River in Atlantic Morocco and (3) a native Atlas Mountains clade which probably arose from a reticulate evolutionary event, following invasion by Atlantic trout that introgressed into local populations.

The drawing of concrete conclusions is complicated, however, because the stocking of hatchery trout appears to have driven significant introgression in some populations. Furthermore, the Salmo trutta complex reaches the southern limit of its natural range in northwest Africa, and most rivers in the region are too warm to support trout populations. Those populations that do exist are mostly confined to high altitude streams and lakes, or perennial headwaters of short Mediterranean rivers. This degree of isolation, coupled with the relatively extreme environmental conditions, has permitted localised adaptation and morphological differentiation which is not necessarily reflected in distinct genetic signatures. In fact, the population inhabiting the Draa River constitutes the only case in which a fully preserved indigenous genetic signature has been detected. Additional research employing a broader genomic survey has therefore been recommended to more clearly elucidate the evolutionary and taxonomic relationships between northwest African Salmo populations.

Salmo pallaryi has not been included in any DNA analysis, but is likely to have belonged to the Atlas Mountains clade given the location of its only known population.

Seddon (2008) noted that it was possibly only a giant form of Pseudocampylaea portosanctana, but both have been found alive on Ilheu de Cima and, according to Wollaston (1878), there are a few other conchological differences besides size.

The species was originally assessed as 'Pseudocampylaea loweii' A. Férussac, 1835, however the correct specific epithet is 'lowii' (E. Neubert pers. comm. 2019).
The five available museum specimens require further comparison with specimens of Nannophrys ceylonensis.
This species is considered distinct from Philautus microtympanum, following Manamendra-Arachchi and Pethiyagoda (2005).
This species is considered distinct from Philautus leucorhinus following Manamendra-Arachchi and Pethiyagoda (2005).

Specimens recorded as Philautus temporalis and P. leucorhinus from the Western Ghats of India are now considered to be P. wynaadensis. P. temporalis and P. leucorhinus are endemic species of Sri Lanka (S.D. Biju and K. Manamendra-Arachchi pers. comm.; Bossuyt and Dubois 2001).
We consider this species to be distinct from Philautus leucorhinus following Manamendra-Arachchi and Pethiyagoda (2005).
This species was resurrected from the synonymy of Philautus microtympanum by Dutta and Manamendra-Arachchi (1996).
This species is considered distinct from Philautus leucorhinus following Manamendra-Arachchi and Pethiyagoda (2005).
This species is considered distinct from Philautus leucorhinus (Günther, 1858) following Manamendra-Arachchi and Pethiyagoda (2005).

Specimens formerly attributed to Philautus temporalis and P. leucorhinus from the Western Ghats are now correctly assigned to P. wynaadensis. P. temporalis and P. leucorhinus are now considered to be endemic species of Sri Lanka (S.D. Biju and K. Manamendra-Arachchi pers. comm.).

Specimens formerly attributed to Philautus variabilis from the Western Ghats of India are now known to be misidentified P. wynaadensis. P. variabilis is endemic to Sri Lanka, where it is now considered to be extinct (K. Manamendra-Arachchi and S.D. Biju pers. comm.).
This species is considered distinct from Philautus microtympanum following Manamendra-Arachchi and Pethiyagoda (2005).

According to Häkkinen (2013), Musa fitzalanii F.Muell. is assigned to Musa sect. Callimusa Cheesman. By this definition, M. fitzalanii is a wild relative of Manila hemp, M. textilis Née., and Fe'i bananas, under Taxon Group 2, and a wild relative of edible crop bananas and plantains under Taxon group 4, according to the taxon group definition by Maxted et al. (2006). However, it should be noted that Häkkinen's classification does not have universal contemporary support (J. Daniells pers. comm. 2020), and recent accounts contend the validity of the ascribed sections (Daniells and Janssens 2020). Additionally, for M. fitzalanii in particular, the decision to reassign the taxon to section Callimusa from the former section Eumusa does not appear to be evidence-based (J. Daniells pers. comm. 2020). At present, though, an alternative contemporary classification scheme has not been formally proposed, so for now this classification is retained to define relatedness to the crop.

Musa fitzalanii has been widely accepted as a distinct species (Ross 1987, Hnatiuk 1990, Häkkinen 2013, Department of the Environment 2020, WCSP 2020). At present, there is insufficient evidence to disprove its specific status; however, it is likewise challenging to prove its taxonomic distinctness (J. Daniells pers. comm. 2020). Simmonds (1956) considered the species likely to be allied to M. schizocarpa and this remains a possibility (J. Daniells pers. comm. 2020). Further research into the taxonomy of the species is necessary, yet availability of suitable genetic material with which to conduct such research may be a limiting factor.

If, as proposed by Cheke (2010), the type locality of Cathetorhinus melanocephalus is on Mauritius, this name is likely to be a senior synonym of the only native blindsnake known from Mauritius, Madatyphlops cairei. This author cautions, however, that it is "not likely to be easy" to demonstrate a connection between the two, as M. cairei is known only from subfossil remains from a site with poor DNA preservation and the C. melanorhinus holotype has been preserved in alcohol for more than 200 years.

Deloneura belongs in the tribe Pentilini not Liptenini. Subtribes are no longer used in the subfamily Poritiinae, so the name Durbaniina should be deleted. Deloneura is not divided into subgenera. The type locality of D. immaculata is "Bashee River, Kaffraria [Eastern Cape Province, South Africa]".
There are no notable issues.
Hemignathus lucidus, H. hanapepe and H. affinis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as H. lucidus following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).

This species (Delissea undulata) was known from two varieties: D. undulata var. undulata and D. u. var. argutidentata. The variety from Hawai'i Island was elevated to D. argutidentata and the variety from Maui was elevated to D. undulata.

Psittacara labati (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Aratinga.

Conures were also reported from Barbados (Clark 1905a) and Martinique (Clark 1905b), but insufficient evidence exists to assign them taxonomically.
This species is known from only two specimens, the holotype collected by E.A. Eastwood in November 1911, and another specimen collected by Vincent A. Wager in December 1928.

There has been confusion regarding the identity of this species in the past. Raw (1973) assigned specimens from the KwaZulu-Natal Midlands to Scelotes guentheri, but these specimens were later described as S. bourquini (Broadley 1994). Because S. guentheri is known from only a single specimen, its taxonomic status remains uncertain, although most authors consider it valid (e.g., FitzSimons 1943, Broadley 1994, Branch 1998). The differences between these species are minor (the presence of a slightly higher ventral scale count, a postnasal scale and the absence of preanal pores) prompting Raw (2021) to suggest that S. bourquini should be synonymised with S. guentheri. However, this conclusion was based on the examination of limited material and therefore requires further data to confirm the result.
This species was recognized as distinct from Atelopus cruciger by Lötters et al. (2004).

The generic placement of this species is uncertain, as it was based on shell characteristics, lacking anatomical data. The species is possibly identical to B. limnopsis according to Boeters (1976).

Glöer et al. (2010) placed the species in genus Pseudamnicola Paulucci, 1878, however this revision has not been adopted.
Was under Iguanidae.

Previously listed as Chlorostilbon bracei (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), but moved to current genus following a recent overhaul of all genera by NACC, based on McGuire et al. (2014), Stiles et al. (2017a, b) and others. Known only from the type specimen, taken in 1877. Fossil hummingbird bones found on New Providence (Graves and Olson 1987) are probably also referable to this species (Olson and Hilgartner 1982). Monotypic.

Previously listed as Chlorostilbon elegans (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), but moved to current genus following a recent overhaul of all genera by NACC, based on McGuire et al. (2014), Stiles et al. (2017a, b) and others. Described from a single specimen, dated 1860; recently shown to be a valid species (Weller 1999). Monotypic.
Aegolius gradyi (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was newly described from fossil remains by Olson (2012).
Bermuteo avivorus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was newly described from fossil deposits by Olson (2008).
Colaptes oceanicus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was recently described from subfossil material by Olson (2013).
Pipilo naufragus (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was newly described from subfossil records by Olson (2012).

This taxon has in the past sometimes been included as a subspecies of Pipistrellus tenuis (Koopman 1973, 1993), but its status has been confirmed by genetic and morphological assessment, which revealed it was a full species endemic to Christmas Island (Helgen et al. 2009).

Govenia floridana was initially identified as the more widespread tropical species Govenia utriculata when discovered in 1957. However, the Florida population differs from G. utriculata in that the sheaths are not inflated, it is nearly polygonal in cross section, the column is prominently winged, and the petals are spotted (Greenwood 1991). Based on these differences, Govenia floridana was established as a distinct species by Brown (2000).

The previous Red List assessments for Galápagos tortoises treated the various allopatric island populations as subspecies of Chelonoidis nigra, as did several authors (Pritchard 1996; Caccone et al. 1999; Beheregaray et al. 2003; Fritz and Havas 2007; TTWG 2007, Rhodin et al. 2008). However, other authors have considered them as full species based on morphology (Bour 1980; Fritts 1983; Ernst and Barbour 1989) and more recently several researchers (Caccone et al. 2002; Russello et al. 2005, 2007; Poulakakis et al. 2008, 2012, 2015; Chiari et al. 2009) have treated most of them as full species based on congruent patterns of mitochondrial and nuclear variation. This elevated species-level taxonomy has been largely accepted by TTWG (2009, 2014) and TEWG (2015) for most phylogenetic lineages of Galápagos tortoises. This Red List assessment therefore now treats C. abingdonii as a full species, rather than retaining its previous subspecies ranking from earlier Red List assessments.

The name Testudo ephippium, athough widely applied to the Pinzón [Duncan Island] Tortoise in the past, was interpreted by Pritchard (1996) to possibly be based on a type specimen from Pinta, and therefore potentially a senior synonym of Testudo abingdonii, but this has not yet been determined genetically.
